1 encouraging, soliciting, or coercing a person to participate in criminal gang activity includes
2 communications created or shared online, including through social media platforms, whether the
3 communications are shared publicly or privately.
4 (b) A violation of this section is a Class F Class D felony.
5 (c) Nothing in this section shall preclude a person who commits a violation of this section
6 from criminal culpability for the underlying offense committed by the minor under any other
7 provision of law."
8 SECTION 3.(c) This section becomes effective December 1, 2026, and applies to
9 offenses committed on or after that date.
10 SECTION 4.(a) Article 13A of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes is amended by
11 adding a new section to read:
12 "§ 14-50.31. Possession of firearm by criminal gang member.
13 (a) It shall be unlawful for any person who has been identified by any court in the State
14 of North Carolina as a member of a criminal gang to purchase, own, possess, or have in the
15 person's custody, care, or control any firearm or any weapon of mass death and destruction as
16 defined in G.S. 14-288.8(c). A person who violates this section is guilty of a Class H felony.
17 (b) For the purposes of this section, a firearm is (i) any weapon, including a starter gun,
18 which will or is designed to or may readily be converted to expel a projectile by the action of an
19 explosive, or its frame or receiver, or (ii) any firearm muffler or firearm silencer. This section
20 does not apply to an antique firearm as defined in G.S. 14-409.11."
21 SECTION 4.(b) Article 13A of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes is amended by
22 adding a new section to read:
23 "§ 14-50.32. Use, carry, or possess a firearm by a member of a criminal gang in relation to
24 or in furtherance of a drug felony or a crime of violence.
25 (a) For the purposes of this section, the following definitions apply:
26 (1) Brandish. – To display all or part of a firearm or otherwise make the presence
27 of the firearm known to another person.
28 (2) Crime of violence. – A crime where there is a use or threatened use of physical
29 force against the person or property of another or that by its nature involves a
30 substantial risk of physical force against the person or property of another in
31 the course of committing the crime.
32 (3) Drug crime. – Any offense that would be chargeable by indictment under
33 Article 5 of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes.
34 (4) Firearm. – Any (i) weapon, including a starter gun, which will or is designed
35 to or may readily be converted to expel a projectile by the action of an
36 explosive, or its frame or receiver, or (ii) firearm muffler or firearm silencer.
37 This term does not include an antique firearm as defined in G.S. 14-409.11.
38 (b) It shall be unlawful for any member of a criminal gang during and in relation to any
39 crime of violence or drug crime for which the person would be chargeable by indictment under
40 the laws of this State to use, carry, or possess a firearm in furtherance of that crime. A violation
41 of this subsection is a Class G felony, unless subsection (c) or (d) of this section applies.
42 (c) If a firearm is brandished during the commission of the offense, then the violation is
43 a Class F felony.
44 (d) If a firearm is discharged during the commission of the offense, then the violation is
45 a Class D felony."
46 SECTION 4.(c) Article 13A of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes is amended by
47 adding a new section to read:
48 "§ 14-50.33. Sell, deliver, give, or transfer a firearm to a member of a criminal gang or to
49 a juvenile by a member of a criminal gang.
50 (a) It shall be unlawful for any person to sell, deliver, give, or otherwise transfer a firearm
51 to a person whom the transferor knows or has reasonable cause to believe is a member of a
House Bill 1173-First Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 criminal gang if the transferor knows or has reasonable cause to believe that the member of the
2 criminal gang intends to carry, possess, discharge, or otherwise use the firearm in the commission
3 of any criminal act listed in G.S. 14-50.16A(2).
4 (b) It shall be unlawful for a member of a criminal gang to sell, deliver, give, or otherwise
5 transfer a firearm to a person whom the criminal gang member knows or has reasonable cause to
6 believe is a juvenile if the member of the criminal gang knows or has reasonable cause to believe
7 that the juvenile intends to carry, possess, discharge, or otherwise use the firearm in the
8 commission of any criminal act listed in G.S. 14-50.16A(2). For purposes of this section, the
9 term "juvenile" means a person who is less than 18 years of age.
10 (c) A violation of this section is a Class G felony."
11 SECTION 4.(d) Article 13A of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes is amended by
12 adding a new section to read:
13 "§ 14-50.34. Use of witness testimony.
14 Criminal gang activity, membership, association, leadership, and existence may be proven
15 through the testimony of a fact witness, an expert witness, or a combined fact expert witness
16 pursuant to Chapter 8C of the General Statutes. In any proceeding pursuant to this Article, expert
17 testimony is admissible to show particular conduct, status, and customs indicative of criminal
18 gangs and criminal gang activity, including any of the following:
19 (1) Characteristics of persons who are members of a criminal gang.
20 (2) Specific rivalries between criminal gangs.
21 (3) Common practices and operations of criminal gangs and members of those
22 criminal gangs.
23 (4) Social customs and behavior of members of criminal gangs.
24 (5) Terminology used by members of criminal gangs.
25 (6) Codes of conduct, including criminal conduct, of particular criminal gangs.
26 (7) The types of crimes that are likely to be committed by a particular criminal
27 gang or by criminal gangs in general."
28 SECTION 4.(e) Article 13A of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes is amended by
29 adding a new section to read:
30 "§ 14-50.35. Venue.
31 In any criminal proceeding brought under this Article, the crime shall be construed to have
32 been committed in any county in which any act was performed as part of criminal gang activity."
33 SECTION 4.(f) This section becomes effective December 1, 2026, and applies to
34 offenses committed on or after that date.
35 SECTION 5.(a) Article 4 of Chapter 8C of the General Statutes is amended by
36 adding a new section to read:
37 "Rule 416. Evidence of criminal gang activity.
38 (a) For purposes of this rule, the term "criminal gang activity" is as defined in
39 G.S. 14-50.16A.
40 (b) In any proceeding in which a person is accused of conducting, participating in, or
41 conspiring to commit criminal gang activity, or in any proceeding under Article 13B of Chapter
42 14 of the General Statutes, evidence of the defendant's commission of criminal gang activity and
43 other crimes, wrongs, or acts shall be admissible and may be considered for its bearing on any
44 matter to which it is relevant.
45 (c) In any proceeding in which the prosecution intends to offer evidence under this rule,
46 the prosecutor shall disclose the evidence to the defendant, including statements of witnesses or
47 a summary of the substance of any testimony that is expected to be offered, at least 10 days in
48 advance of trial, unless the time is shortened or lengthened or pretrial notice is excused by the
49 judge upon good cause shown.
50 (d) This rule shall not be the exclusive means to admit or consider the evidence described
51 in this rule."
